TEM analysis (
                        Fig. 1A and 1B) shows the morphology and particle size of N-BCDs and RCDs. The CDs are spherical and relatively monodisperse, with average diameters of approximately 2.344 nm (N-BCDs) and 3.412 nm (RCDs), respectively. Further high-resolution TEM (HRTEM) images (Figures S2A and S2B) reveal that N-BCDs contain numerous lattice fringes with spacings of 0.21 nm and 0.22 nm, which could be attributed to the (100) plane in graphite or aromatic carbon materials, consistent with the interplanar spacing of carbon materials (Atchudan et al., 2020; 
                        Chen et al., 2024; 
                        Saikia et al., 2022; 
                        Tian et al., 2020). This structural feature confirms the graphite structure of N-BCDs, which enhanced their performance in fluorescence sensing applications. The morphological features of N-BCDs@MIPs are shown in Figures S2D and S2E, revealing a uniformly spherical shape with an average diameter of approximately 295.994 nm. Similarly, Figures S2G and S2H illustrate the spherical morphology of N-BCDs@NIPs, with a more uniform particle size averaging around 266.268 nm. Figures S2F and S2I provide further visualization of the overall morphology of MIPs and NIPs. As displayed in Fig. 1C and S2C, both MIPs and NIPs exhibit a distinct core-shell structure, with the imprinted layer presenting a defined thickness. This core-shell structure design effectively enhanced the recognition capability of the material and improves the selectivity of the sensor.
